(1207, 182, '_elementor_data', '[{\"id\":\"9c08dc2\",\"elType\":\"section\",\"settings\":{\"structure\":\"20\"},\"elements\":[{\"id\":\"1571a7f\",\"elType\":\"column\",\"settings\":{\"_column_size\":50,\"_inline_size\":null},\"elements\":[{\"id\":\"b3835fa\",\"elType\":\"widget\",\"settings\":{\"title\":\"Visitor Centre and Cafe, East India Dock Basin \\u2014 London\",\"title_color\":\"#4A4A4A\",\"typography_typography\":\"custom\",\"typography_font_size\":{\"unit\":\"px\",\"size\":63,\"sizes\":[]},\"typography_font_weight\":\"500\"},\"elements\":[],\"widgetType\":\"heading\"},{\"id\":\"4c819c8\",\"elType\":\"widget\",\"settings\":{\"editor\":\"<p><em><strong>Client<\\/strong><\\/em><br \\/><em>Lea Valley Regional Park Authority<\\/em><\\/p><p><em><strong>Collaborators<\\/strong><\\/em><br \\/><em>Jane Wernick Associates \\/ Northcroft<\\/em><\\/p><p>5th Studio have established a design framework for the creation of a major new park for London \\u2013 the Lea River Park \\u2013 connecting the Olympic Park to the Thames.<\\/p><p>Where the park meets the river, a public building at East India Dock Basin would mark the creation of a vibrant new destination at the end of the 26-mile Lee Valley Regional Park. The design proposed a caf\\u00e9 and spaces for education that would benefit from spectacular views across the Thames, and the capacity to open onto its landscape setting.<\\/p><p>Given the unique site context and the potential for change in the local area, the building is designed as an adaptable container. Rooms are envisaged as multi-use community spaces, capable of hosting a range of events from \\u2018river clean-up\\u2019 events, to corporate away days.<\\/p><p>Situated on the river frontage, the building has been located to ensure minimal impact on the ecology of the nature reserve and also to facilitate a future public riverside walk on the northern side of the Thames.<\\/p>\",\"align\":\"justify\",\"typography_typography\":\"custom\",\"typography_font_weigh